at can be stored, into the setDefaultCommand function of DriveTrain, which it inherits from SubsystemBase.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">m_drivetrain.setDefaultCommand(new RunCommand(() -&gt; m_drivetrain.tankDrive(-driverController.getLeftY(), driverController.getRightX())));
</code></pre>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2023-03-10T01:49:16.597Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":61,"readers_count":60,"score":17.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":429664,"topic_slug":"trouble-with-differential-drive","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":56557,"username":"IHateTuningPID","name":"","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/i/df705f/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":56557,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/trouble-with-differential-drive/429664/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3161465,"name":"Sophia D.","username":"WaspBoi","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/w/ba9def/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-03-10T02:05:15.107Z","cooked":"<p>I’ve corrected most of the errors, though I’m not sure if it will work. At the moment I having trouble in the Drivetrain subsystem to add requirements; as well as I realized the command file tankdrive is not being used and I’m sure that’s an issue.</p>
<p>I’ve updated the code, would you be able to look over it again?</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2023-03-10T02:05:15.107Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":57,"readers_count":56,"score":16.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":429664,"topic_slug":"trouble-with-differential-drive","display_username":"Sophia D.","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":56557,"username":"IHateTuningPID","name":"","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/i/df705f/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":57355,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/trouble-with-differential-drive/429664/4","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3161479,"name":"","username":"IHateTuningPID","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/i/df705f/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-03-10T02:27:54.473Z","cooked":"<p>You don’t really need a command for your differential drive, differential drive is simple enough that it can just be a method which is where the run command comes in, however if you want to apply some things like slew limiting, it might be cleaner to implement it in a command. In the command you are need to pass a drive subsystem into its constructor and store the DriveTrain that gets passed in the class.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">DriveTrain m_driveTrain;

public tankDrive(DriveTrain drivetrain) {
    m_driveTrain = drivetrain;
    // This function right here lets the command scheduler know what
    // subsystems you are using so it doesn't try to access to things at once
    // because when multithreading, which is what the Command Scheduler does,
    // if you try to access the same thing at one time it will cause unknown behavior
    // and things will crash.
    addRequirements(m_driveTrain);
}
</code></pre>
<p>To get this to run you would then need to import this command into RobotContainer and set the default command for the DriveTrain subsystem. It is the only place you should specify a default command until you are very familiar with how the command based system works. It would look like this.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">  public RobotContainer() {
    // Add default command that runs when the drivetrain isn't being used in any
    // other commands, such as an autonomous command that automatically balances.
    m_Drive.setDefaultCommand(new tankDrive(m_Drive));
    // Configure the trigger bindings
    configureBindings();
  }
</code></pre>
<p>Something to note as you are fleshing out your code, it is easier to read code when you name classes like driveSubsystem, or tankDriveCommand. It may help you keep track of what is happening because you have the tankDrive method and the tankDriveCommand.</p>
<p>edit:<br>
Also you need to call the tankDrive method from the object m_driveTrain in the execute method of the command. You will also need to pass in and store a DoubleSupplier into tankDrive command. These do not need to go in the addRequirements function. Then in execute you would pass the values in by calling the getAsDouble() function on the double suppliers. In RobotContainer the constructor would need to look like this:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">m_Drive.setDefaultCommand(new tankDrive(m_Drive, 
    () -&gt; -driverController.getLeftY() /*This is the drive value*/,
    () -&gt; driverController.getRightX() /*This is rotation value*/
);
</code></pre>
<p>As I said earlier lambdas are basically just functions you can store. The parenthesis store arguments of lambda, so they are empty because the functions don’t need any arguments. The → basically just points towards the function body.</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2023-03-10T02:42:09.501Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":50,"readers_count":49,"score":20.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":429664,"topic_slug":"trouble-with-differential-drive","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":3,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":57355,"username":"WaspBoi","name":"Sophia D.","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/w/ba9def/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":56557,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/trouble-with-differential-drive/429664/5","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3161508,"name":"Sophia D.","username":"WaspBoi","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/w/ba9def/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-03-10T03:20:05.320Z","cooked":"<p>I’m sorry to keep asking you questions and for advice. I currently have no errors but when trying to drive it still won’t drive. I think it has to do with my tankDrive command file, though I could most definitely be wrong. I used your advice along with following <a href